@node INTRO "intro"

  I just love my Amiga. No, really! :-) It's only thing that make me
  happy (except my beloved Dorothy & alcohol;-). But Im not the only
  one who have access to my Amiga. There are some other person that
  like to sit infront my Amiga, or just login using a telnet deamon.
  To protect my source code, e-mails and other junk I have installed
  a MultiUserFileSystem. Now I can feel a litte bit secure. But Amiga
  wasn't designed for multiuser pruposes, so there is many backdoors
  to hack, hang, or kill Your system. One day I have loged in from
  x86 running windoze on my Amiga. I saw a normal prompt.

  Sat Jun  9 20:12:42 GMT 2001
  [ opi@bleach /GanjaOS  $ ]

  So I typed @{FG fill}reset@{FG text}. Next thing I saw was a windoze
  request box. "Connection With Amiga Lost". Yes, I have reboot my Amiga.
  And every user can run @{FG fill}reset@{FG text} aswell. I can ofcourse
  change rights, and disallow to run it, but I don't like this kind of job.

  It was very easy to do a muReset command that can be runned only from
  root account. Now, any user that type reset in shell should see:

  Sat Jun  9 20:17:48 GMT 2001
  [ opi@bleach muReset  $ ]mureset
  only root can do that!
  [ opi@bleach muReset  $ ]

  and that's it! If you think I have missed something check @{"future" link future} & @{"author" link author}
  links

@endnode
